FoodBasket = aggregate(cbind(allindia$chicken_v,allindia$pulsestot_v,allindia$Milktotal_v,allindia$MPCE_URP) , by=list(allindia$statex), FUN=mean)
colnames(FoodBasket)= c("State", "Chicken", "Pulses","Milk","MPCE")
library(ineq)
gini_index = (aggregate((allindia$MPCE_URP),by=list(allindia$statex),FUN=Gini))
names(gini_index)
## [1] "Group.1" "x"
colnames(gini_index)= c("State", "Gini")
pov_index = (aggregate((allindia$MPCE_URP),1500,by=list(allindia$statex),FUN=pov))
names(pov_index)
## [1] "Group.1" "x"
colnames(pov_index)= c("State", "Poverty")
VizBasket<- cbind(FoodBasket,pov_index,gini_index)
VizBasket1<-VizBasket[,-c(6,8)]

a- Milk Value

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = indiaF_1, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group,fill = Milk)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red") +  coord_equal()

#highest milk consumption is observed in punjab and least consumption can be observed in Chattisgarh

b - Chicken Value

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = indiaF_1, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group,fill = Chicken)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "blue", high = "pink") +  coord_equal()

c - Pulses Value

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = indiaF_1, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group,fill = Pulses)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "cyan", high = "black") +  coord_equal()

#highest Pulses consumption value is observed in Himachal Pradesh and least consumption can be observed in Manipur and Meghalaya

d - Poverty

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = indiaF_1, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group,fill = Poverty)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "orange", high = "red") +  coord_equal()

# Highest Poverty can be observed in Jharkhand, MP,Bihar,UP,Chattisgarh and least poverty can be observed in punjab, Haryana, Goa and kerala.

e - Income

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = indiaF_1, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group,fill = MPCE)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "purple", high = "blue") +  coord_equal()

#Highest Income can be observed in the Kerala, Punjab, Haryana and Himachal Pradesh

f - Gini

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = indiaF_1, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group,fill = Gini)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "orange", high = "red") +  coord_equal()

#Highest Gini can be observed in kerala followed by himachal pradesh and karnatka.

West Bengal - Urban

#cereals
WB.foodbskt<-aggregate(WB$cerealtot_v,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(WB.foodbskt)[colnames(WB.foodbskt)=="Group.1"] <- "District"
colnames(WB.foodbskt)[colnames(WB.foodbskt)=="x"] <- "cereal"

#pulses
pulses<-aggregate(WB$pulsestot_v,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(pulses)[colnames(pulses)=="x"] <- "pulses"
WB.foodbskt$pulses<-pulses$pulses
# oilseeds
oilseeds<-aggregate(WB$oilseeds_v,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(oilseeds)[colnames(oilseeds)=="x"] <- "oilseeds"
WB.foodbskt$oilseeds<-oilseeds$oilseeds

#vegetable
vegetable<-aggregate(WB$vegtt_v,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(vegetable)[colnames(vegetable)=="x"] <- "vegetable"
WB.foodbskt$vegetable<-vegetable$vegetable

#milk
milk<-aggregate(WB$Milktotal_v,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(milk)[colnames(milk)=="x"] <- "milk"
WB.foodbskt$milk<-milk$milk

#chicken
chicken<-aggregate(WB$chicken_v,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(chicken)[colnames(chicken)=="x"] <- "chicken"
WB.foodbskt$chicken<-chicken$chicken

#MPCE
income<-aggregate(WB$MPCE_URP,by=list(WB$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(income)[colnames(income)=="x"] <- "income"
WB.foodbskt$income<-income$income

#Poverty-choosing respondents with income less than or equal to 1500
pov = WB[WB$MPCE_URP <="1500",]
poverty<-aggregate(pov$MPCE_URP,by=list(pov$District),FUN=mean)
colnames(poverty)[colnames(poverty)=="x"] <- "poverty"
WB.foodbskt$poverty<-poverty$poverty

#Gini
library(ineq)
gini.index<-aggregate(WB$MPCE_URP,by=list(WB$District),FUN=Gini)
colnames(gini.index)[colnames(gini.index)=="x"] <- "gini"
WB.foodbskt$gini<-gini.index$gini
write.csv(WB.foodbskt, file = "WB_foodbskt_urban.csv")

Q3 and Q4.

var.test(Viz1$Chicken,Viz1$MPCE,conf.level = 0.99,alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  Viz1$Chicken and Viz1$MPCE
## F = 0.00035809, num df = 34, denom df = 34, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 99 percent confidence interval:
##  0.0001449108 0.0008848759
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##       0.0003580894
#The p-value observed is p < 2.2e-16.
#Hence, there is significant difference between the two variances.
